I do something similar with Excel files using jq (<a href="http://stedolan.github.io/jq/" rel="nofollow">http://stedolan.github.io/jq/</a>) and j (<a href="https://npmjs.org/package/j" rel="nofollow">https://npmjs.org/package/j</a>):<p><pre><code>    $ j -J sample_data.xlsb tbl | jq &#x27;length&#x27;
    3
    $ j -J sample_data.xlsb tbl | jq &#x27;[.[]|.id]|max&#x27;
    3
    $ j -J sample_data.xlsb tbl | jq &#x27;[.[]|.id]|min&#x27;
    1
    $ j -J sample_data.xlsb tbl | jq &#x27;[.[]|.value]|add&#x27;
    18
</code></pre>
jq syntax is very terse compared to the equivalent SQL
